---
import Layout from '../layouts/Layout.astro';
import Nav from '../components/Nav.astro';
import Footer from '../components/Footer.astro';
---

<Layout title="Details are the product — Johannes Homeier">
  <div class="site">
    <Nav />
    <main>
      <article class="page wrap detail essay measure">
        <a class="backlink" href="/">
          <svg width="14" height="14" viewBox="0 0 24 24" fill="none" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="2" stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round" aria-hidden="true">
            <path d="m12 19-7-7 7-7"/>
            <path d="M19 12H5"/>
          </svg>
          Back
        </a>
        <p class="meta">2026 · 02 · 14 &nbsp;·&nbsp; 2 minute read</p>
        <h1>Details are the product</h1>
        <p>
          People talk about details like a finishing step — the polish you add once the real
          work is done. I've come to believe the opposite. The details <em>are</em> the
          work. They are the part the person on the other side actually touches.
        </p>
        <p>
          A button that settles instead of snapping. Copy with one fewer word than you thought
          you needed. An empty state that says something true. None of these show up in a
          feature list, and all of them are the difference between a tool you tolerate and one
          you trust.
        </p>
        <p>
          The trouble is that details don't announce themselves. You only feel their
          absence, as a small friction you can't name. So the work is mostly noticing —
          using your own thing slowly, on a bad day, and fixing the thing that annoyed you
          instead of explaining it away.
        </p>
        <pre><code>{`// the whole philosophy, roughly
while (annoyed) {
  fix(theSmallestThing);
}`}</code></pre>
        <p>
          It doesn't scale, and that's the point. Care is legible. People can tell
          when someone sat with a thing until it was right — and that feeling, more than any
          feature, is what they come back for.
        </p>
      </article>
    </main>
    <Footer />
  </div>
</Layout>
